				<div class="postbody">
				Well,
<br />

<br />
The idea is to make him get a critic mind and find arguments for something he is against(this is why the controversial subjects)...however, the teacher need to keep his authority and if a student dont do what is asked to do, it is undermining his authority.
<br />

<br />
I would suggest you talk with the teacher.  Talking with the principal would most likely be doing more harm to your teen then help, remember, he is stuck with this teacher until June(and changing class is prolly even worser), and if the teacher is a bad teacher, well odd is you dont wanna get that teacher resentfull.
<br />

<br />
The subject is prolly openly proposed by the school district and the teacher is prolly just following those recommendations.  The subject is appropriate for grade 9 kids, they should be talking about capitalism, communist as well, marriages and all those subjects are appropriate at this age.  Yes yes, death penalty as well.
<br />

<br />
This subject have 1 huge flaw, your teen can be subject to others teens teases, and I would argue with the teacher about this.  Make him defend drugs, complete blind patriotism, whatever is virile and he is against would have much better results IMO.  A girl would prolly not be affected as bad with having to defend such a subject, throwing this on a little guy is a pretty bad idea, for socials reasons with the rest of the group(eh, he will be tease all the remaining of the year because of that, have no doubts there).
<br />

<br />
I was a social study teacher(in french of course) as well for grade 9, and I think teens need more choices, however, I am busy playing MMORPGs now so your stuck the bottom of the barrel teachers!  *grin evilly*
<br />

<br />
PS: If you kindly, quietly, endlessly, deploy tons of efforts to talk and argue with the teacher, I think it is the best way, require lot of efforts, but most likely the best way to get you result.  Can leave a message for the teacher to call you back every day or whatever...now if you are to outburst, you should just go to the principal, insulting or been rude with the teacher is certainly not going to help, no matter how ''objective'' the teacher claim to be.  I can tell you if the teacher get tired to see you but you are always quiet and calm(and not insulting), this should work pretty well, they are already overburdened.
<br />

<br />
PPS: If your teen do it nonetheless, you could always play, nicely, the guilty card against that teacher, and make him understand how miserable your teen feel because of that(even if not true, you can exagerate a little).  The teacher is human, and if the teacher feel guilty toward your teen ''mistreatment'', well, this is an edge for your teen...see, a social study teacher judge texts, aguments, even if they try to be objectives, well, if they feel guilty, it will slightly help your teen(he will still need to work hard, but it can help get better results, having 1 point more here and there, because the teacher will be looking more to find valids points he otherwise could have miss with a faster correction, it is not cheating,it is getting favorable attention).<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
